notesStmt.note: This is an illuminated and illustrated copy of the Ḫamse (quintet) of the Ottoman Turkish poet and scholar ʿAṭāʾullāh bin Yaḥyá ʿAṭāʾī (d. 1044 AH / 1634 CE). Although different in content, this work takes its inspiration from the famous Persian Khamsah of Niẓāmī Ganjavī (d. 605 AH / 1209 CE) and the Khamsah of Amīr Khusraw Dihlavī (d. 725 AH / 1325 CE). This Ottoman copy of ʿAṭāʾī's work ends with a portion of his Dīvān (fols. 142b-151b) instead of the fifth poem (mesnevi), Ḥilyet ül-efkār. The text, written in nastaʿlīq script, was copied by Ḫeyrullah Ḫeyrī Çāvuşzade in 1133 AH / 1721 CE. There are thirty-eight illustrations, and illuminated incipits introduce the different poems (fols. 1b, 22b, 63b, 107b, and 142b). The brown leather binding is original to the manuscript.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Turkish, Ottoman (1500-1928).

خمسۂ عطاۓ

title.note: Title inscribed on fol. 1a and tail edge

msItem.note: Contains: Sāḳīnāme, also known as ʿĀlemnumā (fols. 1b-21b), Nefḥat ül-ezhār (fols. 22b-62b), Sobḥet ül-ebkār (fols. 63b-106b), Heft-ḫvān (fols. 107b-141a), and a portion of Dīvān (fols. 142b-151b, incomplete at end); Sāḳīnāme composed in 1024 AH / 1615 CE (see chronosticon on fol. 20b, col. 2, line 11); Nefḥat ül-ezhār composed in 1034 AH / 1624-5 CE (see date given in abjad: dāl lām ghayn, fol. 61b, col. 1, line 16); Sobḥet ül-ebkār composed in 1033 AH / 1623-4 CE (see chronosticon on fol. 106a); Heft-ḫvān composed in 1036 AH / 1626-7 CE (see fol. 141a, col. 2, line 5)

colophon.note: Fol. 62b: al-ḥamd li-Llāh ʿalá al-tamām wa-ʿlá rasūlih wa-<ā>lih afḍal al-ṣalāh wa-al-salām /1/ ʿalá yad afqar al-wará Khayr Allāh Jāwush zādah mattaʿanā Allāh /2/ bi-al-ḥusná wa-ziyādah [sic] qad waqaʿa al-farāgh min taḥrīr hadhihi /3/ al-nuskhah al-sharīfah fī waqt al-ḍuḥá yawm al-jumʿah /4/ min awāsiṭ Rajab al-murajjab li-sanat thal<ā>th /5/ wa-thalathīn wa-mi<ʾ>ah wa-alf min /6/ hijrah [sic] al-nabawīyah /7/ m (= tamma) /8/

Two colophons (fols. 21a and 62b): the first (in Turkish) giving a fuller name of the scribe; the second (in Arabic) giving the name of the scribe as Khayr Allāh Jāwush Zādah and the date of copying as Friday, mid Rajab 1133 AH / 1721 CE

supportDesc.foliation: One or more folios missing after fol. 143

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in black and gold

handDesc.handNote: Written in nastaʿlīq script in black ink with chapter headings in red

decoDesc.decoNote: Thirty-eight illustrations; five incipits with illuminated headpieces (fols. 1b, 22b, 63b, 107b, and 142b)

decoNote.title: Incipit page with illuminated headpiece
Ottoman fleet
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts the Ottoman fleet, led by Hüseyn Paşa, setting out from the Black Sea against the Polish army.

decoNote.title: Ottoman Turks fighting the Polish army
View of the Bosphorus Strait
Incipit page with illuminated headpiece
Battle between the Ottoman and Hungarian armies
Sultan Murad IV receiving homage from his subjects
The poet ʿAṭāʾī reading from his book (Ḫamse) to his master
A Christian girl on her deathbed after converting to Islam
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts the story of a Muslim boy who fell in love with a Christian girl. Unable to unite with her, he dies of grief. His friend delivers the bad news to her, and she converts to Islam in the hopes of being united with her Muslim lover in heaven.

decoNote.title: Şeyh Nizameddin saving the life of Hüsrev-i Hindi
Şeyh Gülşeni setting out with his disciples on a voyage
Şeyh Baba and his men
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts Şeyh Baba and his men capturing a group of brigands who robbed their tekke (dervish lodge).

decoNote.title: The poet ʿAṭāʾī talking to a learned man in a tavern
An assassin sent by the king of Yemen searching for Hatem
An imam who put ink, rather than rosewater, on his face
A juriconsult giving sexual advice
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts a mufti, having heard a complaint from a mother about her son-in-law’s inability to consummate his marriage to her daughter, giving sexual advice.

decoNote.title: An adulterous husband and his lover butted by a ram
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts an adulterous husband and his lover being unexpectedly butted by a ram into a room full of surprised guests.

decoNote.title: Two men caught in bed together
A pederast
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts a crowd watching a juggler, while punishment is being meted out to a homosexual for his advances on a young boy. The punished figure on the ground is damaged.

decoNote.title: A sodomite disgraced
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts a sodomite being disgraced before a crowd by drums and a Turkish wind instrument (zurna).

decoNote.title: A thief being bitten by a snake
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts a thief being bitten by a snake while trying to steal the purse of a man dining with friends.

decoNote.title: Incipit page with illuminated headpiece
Musicians entertaining Sultan Murad IV
A messenger from Seljuk Sultan Melikşāh being received by the Byzantine king
Plato in a cave with his followers bringing their self-portraits for examination
Meeting of the armies of Alexander the Great and the Emperor of China
Two lovers spared from being beheaded due their loyalty for each other
A shamed man who lied about a three-day journey from Mecca to Nishapur
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts a man embarrassed by his turban falling off to reveal his bald head. When he protests that his virtue is gone, Mansur replies that it was already gone when he previously lied about his miraculous three-day journey from Mecca to Nishapur.

decoNote.title: An innocent youth being entertained by a group of sodomites
A man exposing himself through a hole in the fence
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts a man exposing himself through a hole in the fence while the women on the other side tie his penis with a string.

decoNote.title: Caliph Maʾmūn and his soldiers being greeted by a man with a tray of fruit
Incipit page with illuminated headpiece
A learned man
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts a learned man, who became ill with desperation after having fallen in love, being entertained by his friends with love stories.

decoNote.title: Hurşid, a Chinese ruler, watching his vizier’s young son swim in a pool
decoNote.note: This illustration depicts Hurşid, a Chinese ruler, watching Behzād, his vizier’s young and handsome son, swimming in a pool. The painting has been torn.

decoNote.title: Sultan Mahmud on horseback speaking with Ayaz
Sultan Mahmud killing a lion and a dragon
A king looking at a picture of his son and his tutor, who fell in love with him
A young man looking out of the window for his lover Abdullah
Mahzun, on his way to visit the emir’s son, being thrown down the stairs by one of the courtiers
Tahir and Tayyib being rescued by a Christian ship
Tayyib and Tahir at a party with their rescuers in European attire
The ship carrying Tahir and Tayyib being greeted by two Christian nobles in a boat
Incipit page with illuminated headpiece
